english:
  title: A Letter of Instruction to the Crown Prince Seongyeong Upon His Passing
  author: Byeon Gye-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The King speaks thus:

    That lifespans are unequal is the decree of Heaven, and cannot be altered. That the deepest bond between father and son springs from Heaven's nature cannot be resisted. This is what dwells eternally in the human heart, what fate has predetermined before time began.

    You were born in the year of Eulyu, and now fourteen years have passed. Not a single day have you strayed from my side. When I wished to dine, you tasted first. When I desired to watch archery, you followed in attendance. In all my comings and goings, I was always with you. Now it is finished. How can I steady my heart? Alas, my grief knows no bounds.

    Your bearing was pure and dignified, without blemish. Your mind was keen and your manner gracious; you practiced filial piety and brotherhood. You studied the classics diligently, and your arrows found their mark repeatedly. I arranged a marriage for you and conferred upon you the title of Crown Prince, believing you would grow to manhood and bring comfort to my declining years. Alas, it is ended. What can be done? What can be done?

    When you first fell ill, I deemed it but a child's common ailment. Yet when the sickness deepened, what use was regret? Was it my negligence in prayer? The physician's error? Your bright face still hovers before my eyes; your clear voice still rings in my ears. Alas, my sorrow is boundless.

    Your mother and I weep for you without measure. Yet you, in your filial devotion, thought of us even as you departed this life. How can such longing ever cease, even in the springs below?

    You fulfilled your duty as my son—both filial and gifted, wanting nothing. The brevity or length of life is Heaven's decree, not your failing. What have you to regret? But I, your father—I could not oversee the wrapping of your burial garments, could not touch your coffin as you were placed within it, could not gaze upon your tomb as you were laid to rest. Though I am lord of ten thousand chariots, I am brought lower than the common man grieving his child. It is not that I lack feeling, but that circumstance forbids it. My anguish—where does it end?

    Therefore I command that your rank be elevated, that an honorific name be bestowed upon you, that honors flow to you exceeding the common measure. I send my trusted minister to Jindan Temple to commission water and land ceremonies for your peace in the afterlife, and offer these meager libations with this eulogy.

    Alas—words have limits, yet feelings cannot be exhausted. Do you know this? Or do you not know?
  footnotes:
    - Seongyeong was the Crown Prince of Sejong the Great; this is a royal eulogy composed after his death.
    - The 'year of Eulyu' refers to 1441 in the Korean calendar.
    - Water and land ceremonies (수륙, suryuk) are Buddhist rituals performed for the benefit of the deceased.
    - The phrase 'ten thousand chariots' (천승) is a classical expression for sovereign power.
